I now have everything I need. The snapshot has given me the full picture — `src/proxy.ts`, `next.config.ts`, and `src/lib/company-session.ts` are all visible and the bug is unambiguous. Here is the complete diagnosis.

---

## Diagnosis

The proxy is **never invoked for `/api/internal/*` requests** — not because of a matcher problem, but because of a **logic error inside `proxy.ts` itself**. The early-exit guard on line 18 of `src/proxy.ts` unconditionally passes through *every* path that starts with `/api`:

```ts
// src/proxy.ts  (current — broken)
if (pathname.startsWith("/admin") || pathname.startsWith("/api")) {
  return NextResponse.next();   // ← /api/internal/* falls in here and is freed immediately
}
```

`/api/internal/anything` satisfies `pathname.startsWith("/api")`, so the function returns `NextResponse.next()` before it ever reaches the session check. The matcher is fine — it **does** include `/api/internal/*`. The bypass is entirely self-inflicted in the guard logic.

---

## Root Cause — AP-SBA-001 · "Overly-broad static bypass"

This is the classic **Overly-broad Static Bypass** anti-pattern: a prefix guard written to exempt one group of routes (Payload CMS's own `/api` surface) is expressed as a blanket `startsWith("/api")`, which silently absorbs every sub-tree added later, including `/api/internal/*`. Because the guard is evaluated before authentication, it creates an **unauthenticated shortcut** into any route handler whose path happens to share the exempted prefix.

The breakage surfaced during the Next.js 16 upgrade because the upgrade was the moment `/api/internal/*` routes were added to the project — the bug existed from day one but there was nothing under `/api/internal/` to expose it on Next.js 15.

---

## Fix

### 1. Tighten the bypass to exactly the Payload-owned paths (`src/proxy.ts`)

Enumerate the specific prefixes Payload CMS actually needs, instead of carpeting all of `/api`. Payload's built-in endpoints are `/api/` (its REST surface) **and** the Next.js adapter's `/next/` sub-path — nothing else.

```ts
// src/proxy.ts  (fixed)
import { NextResponse } from "next/server";
import type { NextRequest } from "next/server";
import { verifySessionValue, COOKIE_NAME } from "@/lib/company-session";

// Paths that must never be intercepted by session auth.
// Be explicit — a blanket /api bypass silently absorbs any
// new sub-tree you add under /api later (AP-SBA-001).
const ALWAYS_PUBLIC: Array<(p: string) => boolean> = [
  // Payload CMS admin UI
  (p) => p.startsWith("/admin"),
  // Payload's own REST + GraphQL API (ends with a slash to prevent
  // /api/internal from matching — Payload mounts at /api/ not /api)
  (p) => p === "/api" || p.startsWith("/api/"),   // ← REMOVE THIS LINE too; see note below
  // Login flow — visitors must reach the welcome / login page
  (p) => p.startsWith("/for/") || p === "/for",
  // Next.js internals and static assets are already excluded by
  // the matcher, but guard defensively here as well.
  (p) =>
    p.startsWith("/_next/") ||
    p.startsWith("/images/") ||
    p.startsWith("/media/") ||
    p.startsWith("/videos/") ||
    pathname === "/favicon.ico" ||
    pathname === "/robots.txt" ||
    pathname === "/sitemap.xml",
];
```

Wait — Payload's REST surface **is** under `/api/`, so we still need to exempt some of it. The correct split is: exempt Payload's known sub-paths, but **not** `/api/internal`:

```ts
// src/proxy.ts  (final, correct version)
import { NextResponse } from "next/server";
import type { NextRequest } from "next/server";
import { verifySessionValue, COOKIE_NAME } from "@/lib/company-session";

/** Payload CMS mounts its REST API under these exact prefixes. */
const PAYLOAD_API_PREFIXES = [
  "/api/globals/",
  "/api/collections/",  // if you use the default collection REST paths
  // add any other Payload-generated endpoints here as you discover them,
  // OR — better — move Payload to a dedicated basePath (see step 2).
];

function isPublic(pathname: string): boolean {
  // Payload admin UI
  if (pathname.startsWith("/admin")) return true;

  // Payload REST / GraphQL — only the known Payload sub-paths
  for (const prefix of PAYLOAD_API_PREFIXES) {
    if (pathname.startsWith(prefix)) return true;
  }

  // Login flow
  if (pathname.startsWith("/for/") || pathname === "/for") return true;

  // Static assets (belt-and-suspenders; matcher already excludes most of these)
  if (
    pathname.startsWith("/_next/") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/images/") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/media/") ||
    pathname.startsWith("/videos/") ||
    pathname === "/favicon.ico" ||
    pathname === "/robots.txt" ||
    pathname === "/sitemap.xml"
  )
    return true;

  return false;
}

export function proxy(request: NextRequest) {
  const { pathname } = request.nextUrl;

  if (isPublic(pathname)) return NextResponse.next();

  // --- Everything below here is session-gated, including /api/internal/* ---

  const sessionCookie = request.cookies.get(COOKIE_NAME)?.value;
  if (!sessionCookie) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL("/for/welcome", request.url));
  }

  const company = verifySessionValue(sessionCookie);
  if (!company) {
    return NextResponse.redirect(new URL("/for/welcome", request.url));
  }

  const requestHeaders = new Headers(request.headers);
  requestHeaders.set("x-company", company);

  return NextResponse.next({ request: { headers: requestHeaders } });
}

export const config = {
  matcher: [
    "/((?!_next/static|_next/image|favicon.ico|sitemap.xml|robots.txt).*)",
  ],
};
```

### 2. (Strongly recommended) Give Payload its own `basePath` so the collision is structurally impossible (`next.config.ts`)

The cleanest long-term fix is to move Payload's API off the shared `/api` mount point entirely. With Payload 3 + the `withPayload` adapter you can configure `apiBasePath`:

```ts
// next.config.ts
import type { NextConfig } from "next";
import { withPayload } from "@payloadcms/next/withPayload";

const nextConfig: NextConfig = {
  transpilePackages: ["@yilangaodesign/design-system"],
  images: {
    remotePatterns: [
      {
        protocol: "https",
        hostname: "lrjliluvnkciwnyshexq.supabase.co",
        pathname: "/storage/v1/object/public/**",
      },
      { protocol: "https", hostname: "i.ytimg.com" },
    ],
  },
};

export default withPayload(nextConfig, {
  // Payload's REST + GraphQL live under /cms/api — completely separate
  // from your /api/* application routes.
  // Update your Payload config's `serverURL` and any client SDK calls
  // to match this new path.
  apiBasePath: "/cms",
});
```

Once this is in place, your proxy bypass shrinks to a single unambiguous prefix and the `/api/internal/*` collision is structurally impossible:

```ts
// isPublic() becomes trivially safe:
if (pathname.startsWith("/admin")) return true;
if (pathname.startsWith("/cms"))   return true;  // all of Payload
```

---

## Principle

**Be maximally specific in security bypass rules.** Every route you exempt from authentication must be justified by name, not by prefix family. "Allow all `/api` traffic because Payload lives there" is an implicit allowlist that grows silently as you add new routes. The pattern to reach for is:

> **Deny by default, allow by exact enumeration** — if you find yourself writing `startsWith("/api")` in a guard, stop and ask "which `/api` sub-paths specifically need to bypass auth, and why?" If the answer is a closed, enumerable set, list them. If it is genuinely open-ended, restructure the URL space (step 2 above) so the Payload-owned namespace and your application namespace share no common prefix.
